{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The generated function signature matches the expected interface (parameter names, types, return type) specified in the description.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP is the key boundary: this behavior is about whether the real model maps natural language requirements to the correct signature. A stubbed model would always return fixture code and can hide real signature-generation failures. MULTI-STEP is not required here because the behavior can be validated on a single generation step. Rejected Workflow based on behavior text: it only asks that \"generated function signature matches...\" and does not require a multi-step agent loop.","test_description":"Run the real model on a set of interface-spec prompts, parse the generated function signature, and compare parameter names/types/return type to expected definitions. Fail on any mismatch.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"A lower-level stub test would only validate parser/comparator logic, not model signature correctness.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.7,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Orchestration executes attempts in order and returns immediately on the first passing attempt.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS points to module handoff: attempt scheduler, test-result evaluator, and return logic must interact correctly. In-process fakes can reproduce fail->pass sequences and detect ordering/early-exit bugs. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) no required real OS/network/subprocess in behavior text, (b) no dependence on model output quality, (c) no required multi-agentic chain, (d) this is orchestration logic, not model-decision correctness. Rejected System/Agentic/Workflow based on text: \"executes attempts in order and returns immediately\" is control-flow behavior.","test_description":"Wire orchestrator with deterministic fake generator and fake test runner producing [fail, fail, pass]. Assert attempts run strictly in order, stop at first pass, and no extra attempt is executed.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test requires module wiring (not just one pure function), but no real infra or live LLM.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For a function that a single call usually fails, the live iterative loop can still produce a passing implementation within the allowed attempts.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This explicitly requires a live iterative loop with multiple model decisions across attempts, so MULTI-STEP + LLM-DEP are both true. A mocked model hides whether refinement actually improves outcomes across steps. Because multiple real agentic steps are sequenced (generate -> test feedback -> refine -> retest), Workflow is the minimum.","test_description":"Run the live end-to-end loop on a known hard prompt where one-shot success is low; verify the service can still reach a passing implementation within <=3 attempts in at least one run under the defined test condition.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Agentic single-call testing is insufficient because the behavior is explicitly iterative.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.2,"Workflow":0.65}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When tests fail, the refinement prompt builder includes the failed test names and failure messages in the next LLM prompt.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure mode is data handoff between test execution results and prompt-construction modules. This is beyond a single pure function when verifying real wiring from failure artifacts into the next prompt payload. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) no mandatory real OS/network/subprocess to validate inclusion logic, (b) no need for real model output quality, (c) no multi-agentic sequence required for this assertion, (d) handoff is local module orchestration and can be tested deterministically. Rejected Agentic/Workflow because behavior text is about prompt content inclusion, not model decision quality.","test_description":"Simulate a failed attempt with concrete failing test names/messages from the test-result module, build the next prompt through the real orchestration path, and assert those fields appear correctly in the refinement prompt payload.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Unit-only prompt-template tests can miss dropped fields at the module boundary.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The next live attempt changes implementation content in response to prior failure context rather than resubmitting the same code.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This depends on two sequential real model decisions and the handoff of failure context into the next generation step. Deterministic-assertion trap applies: even if assertion is \"code changed,\" a stub cannot verify whether LLM steering caused the change. MULTI-STEP is explicit (prior attempt -> failure context -> next live attempt), so Workflow is required.","test_description":"Execute two live attempts on a case with an initial failure, capture attempt-1 and attempt-2 code, and assert attempt-2 is materially different and aligned with failure context (not a duplicate resubmission).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Single-call Agentic tests miss the sequential handoff dependency.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.26,"Workflow":0.65}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"The service stops after 3 failed attempts and returns a structured error with all three attempts and their test results.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Behavior is orchestration/bookkeeping across generator, test-result collector, and error formatter. Deterministic fakes can drive three failures and validate structure/completeness. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) no explicit need for real OS/network/subprocess to validate stop-at-3 and payload shape, (b) no dependence on model output quality, (c) no required multi-agentic chain for correctness of this behavior, (d) this is state handoff/bookkeeping, not model judgment. Rejected System/Agentic/Workflow based on text focusing on \"stops after 3 failed attempts\" and structured error contents.","test_description":"Use wired modules with deterministic failing generator/test outcomes for three attempts; assert loop terminates at exactly 3 and returned error contains all three attempt records and associated test results.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Lower-level tests would miss integration bugs in attempt aggregation.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"The full non-agentic pipeline wiring (generate call, test execution, attempt bookkeeping) works end to end with deterministic stubbed model outputs.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA is required because \"full ... pipeline\" includes real test execution, which commonly depends on subprocess/filesystem behavior. Mocking test execution can hide failures in command invocation, exit-code handling, temp files, and artifact capture. Rejected Agentic via explicit behavior text: \"non-agentic\" and \"deterministic stubbed model outputs\" disqualify dependence on real model judgment. Workflow is disqualified because no live multi-agentic decisions are required.","test_description":"Run the service end-to-end with a deterministic stub model but real test runner execution against an actual temporary test suite/project on disk; verify generate->execute->bookkeeping flow and final status are correct.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Integration with mocked runner can miss real subprocess/filesystem failures.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.28,"System":0.62,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":8,"description":"The full live loop (generate, test, refine, retest) solves at least one known hard function that fails in the first attempt.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This is an explicit multi-step live agent loop with repeated model decisions and feedback-driven refinement. Correctness depends on real LLM output quality across steps, not just plumbing. Because multiple agentic stages are sequenced end-to-end, Workflow is the minimum required level.","test_description":"Execute the live service on a curated hard function/task with real model calls and real test execution; verify first attempt fails and a later attempt within the 3-attempt limit passes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Any lower level would replace either live model behavior or sequential refinement dynamics.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.15,"Workflow":0.75}}]}
